smooth.Human Rights as War by Other Means traces the use of rights discourse in Northern Ireland's politics from the local civil rights campaigns of the 1960s to present-day activism for truth recovery and LGBT equality. Combining firsthand ethnographic reportage with historical research, Jennifer Curtis analyzes how rights discourse came to permeate grassroots politics and activism, how it transformed those politics, and how rights discourse was in turn transformed. This ethnographic history foregrounds the stories of ordinary people in Northern Ireland who embraced different rights politics and laws to conduct, conclude, and, in some ways, continue the conflict—a complex portrait that challenges the dominant postconflict narrative of political and social abuses vanquished by a collective commitment to human rights. As Curtis demonstrates, failure to critique the appropriation of rights discourse in the peace process perpetuates perilous conditions for a fragile peace and generates flawed prescriptions for other conflicts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman rightsxPolitical aspectszNorthern Ireland. 0aPeace-buildingzNorthern IrelandzNorthern Ireland. 0aPeace-buildingzNorthern Ireland. 0aPolitical violencezNorthern Ireland. 0aSocial conflictzNorthern Ireland. 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aSociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220987740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209877423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover